Part I - Prosper Loan Data¶

by Josh Moore¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains information about individuals who have received personal loans from Prosper between 2005 and 2014. This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,9374 loans detailed in this dataset with 81 different variables for each loan. There is information on the borrow's income, location, credit scores, and overall credit health. This dataset also includes loan rates for the borrower as well as the yields and profits of the lender. Most of these values are numerical but there are a few variables that have string values.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features that I am most interested in is which aspects of a borrower's financial health affect the loan they can get.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think I'll need to focus in on the borrower's financial information. Specifically their income, credit score, employment status, debt-to-income ratio, etc. I'll also need to capture the loan interest rate, term and loan amount.

I'm going to do some initial cleaning of the dataset

# Further cleaning of outliers in LoanOriginalAmount

def remove_outliers_by_group(df, group_col, target_col):
    def iqr_filter(group):
        Q1 = group[target_col].quantile(0.30)
        Q3 = group[target_col].quantile(0.69)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
        return group[(group[target_col] >= lower) & (group[target_col] <= upper)]
    
    return df.groupby(group_col, group_keys=False).apply(iqr_filter)

loan_df = remove_outliers_by_group(loan_df, 'IncomeRange', 'LoanOriginalAmount')

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

I started with looking at the overall 'BorrowerAPR' in the data. The first graph showed the data but due to the overall quantity, it was hard to determine how many loans there were with the APRs between 0.0 and 0.06 and .4+. I changed the y-axis from a linear scale to a logarithmic scale so we can see that data.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

For the 'EmploymentStatus' variable, it wasn't the best set of data that I thought there was originally. I actually question the data and if it is actually accurate based on the borrower's responses. I'm not sure what the question was during the loan application process but one person could have chosen 'employed' as their response but they were full-time as well. I don't think I plan to use the variable 'EmploymentStatus' because of the potential inaccuracy.

For the Borrower's Income Range pie chart, when I first charted it, there was a "Not Displayed" value for a few loans that I didn't catch during the initial cleaning. I saw it on the first iteration of the pie chart so I had to go back to my cleaning stage, remove all loans with the "Not Displayed" value and re-chart the graph.

Bivariate Exploration¶

Now that I have some understanding of some general relationships of this dataset, I'm going to start digging into more speicifc data in regards to my original interest of how much of a borrowers financial health affects their loan details.

My first comparison I want to look at is a borrower's DTI to loan amount.

Here we see the general trend is that the vast majority of loans are issued to people with debt ratios less than 2 which seems reasonable. DTI ratios of 10 seem to be an error in the data that would need to be investigated further with the author or company that this data came from.

Finally for the last bivariate graph, I want to see if there is a relationship between the APR and the total loan amount.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

In the Debt-to-Income vs loan amount scatterplot shows a lot of loans issued in the Debt-To-Income ratio of 10. That seems highly unsual for a lender to loan money to a borrower with such a high DTI. Additional questions would need to be asked with the author of this data to confirm if these values are accurate or not.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

In the loan amount vs income range box plot showed several outliers in the $1-24,999 and $25,000-$49,999 income ranges. The $50,000+ ranges had zero outliers which showed the lender's consistency with loans for borrowers with those income levels. The outliers reveal that there is inconsistancy for loans issued in these income ranges. There are a few outliers in the $1-24,999 income range that have loans around $25,000. That seems fairly risky for a lender to issue that loan.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Using the correlation matrix chart, the borrower's credit score was moderately inversely correlated to the loan APR. This is evidence that helps support my interest in this data set.

Another relationship is the smaller the loan amount the higher the APR.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

One of the relationships that was interesting to me is homeownership and loan amount. In general, when comparing against other borrowers with similar income ranges, Prosper will lend more money to borrowers who own their own homes than those who don't.

Conclusions¶

Before exploring through this data set, I had a good idea that the borrower's credit score was going to correlate in some way with the details of the loan that they received. This is a common way lenders decide who they are going to give loans to. One thing I didn't consider was how much owning a home has an affect on the loan amount and APR.

There are some variables that I thought would correlate but don't appear to at all. One set of those was the total credit inquiries compared with the APR or loan amount.
